{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5e6e766-d87f-428a-9d8e-2084032668ac","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod, Ignore(\"Blocked by #1234\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by #1234\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test, Ignore(\"Blocked by #1234\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test, Skip(\"Blocked by #1234\")]\npublic async Task MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\nNote: xUnit doesn't have a standalone skip attribute — the reason is set directly on `[Fact]` or `[Theory]`. All four frameworks will report skipped tests distinctly from passed/failed in test results.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"702efd24-5d30-4ae7-908d-f683edc80d89","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"5C5D:2CDF90:1B1FD7:218F5F:69F54ECC"},"id":"0ca2b564-77bc-477d-8433-ffc5bbf43424","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:09:41.047Z","parentId":"1375c8fe-61bf-4149-b436-1216627c7947"}
